 {
 "String": "DRINKING WATER: A contaminated drinking water well in New York contained 540 ppb of cyclohexane(1). A public drinking water supply in East Anglia, England that was 210 meters from a leaking petroleum storage tank contained 0.01 ppb cyclohexane and the groundwater 10 and 110 meters from the tank were 10 and <1 ppb, respectively(2). Cyclohexane was found in 5 of 14 waterworks sampled in the UK(3); the sources of the cyclohexane-tainted drinking water were rivers, reservoirs and groundwater, and the contaminate was present in raw, as well as treated water(3). Cyclohexane was detected in 20 of 86 bottled spring water samples, 1 of 61 bottled mineral water samples and 2 of 35 miscellaneous bottled waters in Canada in 1990 at average (range) concentrations of 42.2 (3-108), 3, and 27.6 (8.1-47) ug/kg, respectively(4). In a review of the open literature, cyclohexane was listed as one of the organic compounds most commonly found in drinking water wells(5); the highest concentration found was 540 ppb(5).",
