 "String": "The rate constant for the vapor-phase reaction of n-hexane with photochemically-produced hydroxyl radicals is 5.61X10-12 cu cm/molecule-sec at 25 °C(1). This corresponds to an atmospheric half-life of about 24 hours at an atmospheric concentration of 5X10+5 hydroxyl radicals per cu cm(1). Vapor-phase transport of n-hexane, present at 7% weight as part of a mixture of 13 volatile fuel compounds, including methyl tert-butyl ether, was studied in large-scale lysimeter representing a depth of 2.3 m thick sandy unsaturated zone over a gravel aquifer and studied for 70 days. The initial concentration in vapor was 48.1 g/cu m at 20 °C(2). n-Hexane is not expected to undergo hydrolysis in the environment due to the lack of functional groups that hydrolyze under environmental conditions(3). n-Hexane does not contain chromophores that absorb at wavelengths >290 nm(3) and, therefore, is not expected to be susceptible to direct photolysis by sunlight(SRC).",
