 "Value": {
 "StringWithMarkup": [
 {
 "String": "INDOOR: n-Hexane was identified in 51% of the indoor air samples and 41% of the outdoor air samples taken in Chicago, IL(1). The respective minimum, maximum and average indoor air concentrations of n-hexane for 14 homes and a small office building were 3, 590 and 71 ug/cu m; air samples were collected from 1983-1984 in Ispra (Varese), a region in Northern Italy(2). n-Hexane mean concentrations within and around new and established suburban dwellings sampled in Melbourne, Australia were as follows: non-complaint (i.e. healthy) dwellings: 61 air samples; 22 buildings; 3.2 ug/cu m; complaint dwellings: 11 air samples, 5 buildings; 1.5 ug/cu m; associated outdoor: 37 air samples; 27 sites; 1.6 ug/cu m. Testing took place in summer/early autumn(3). Concentrations within a new dwelling were as follows (ug/cu m; 2, 19, 72, 246 days after construction): living room 200, 16, 4,9, <0.5; bedroom 300, 20, <3, <0.5. Associated outdoor concentrations were 0.4, 0.7 and <0.5 ug/cu m on 2, 19 and 246 days following construction(3). The compound was detected in renovated area and upstairs area of an office building as follows (days since construction commenced;ug/cu m): 2100, 680 at 14 days; 840, 480 at 15 days; and 12, 13 at 81 days(3). In a survey of 100 urban and rural New Jersey homes, 75 samples were above the MDL limit (typically between 0.5 and 3 ug/cu m). A mean concentration of 8.42 ug/cu, minimum of 0.7 ug/cu m, and a maximum concentration of 270 ug/cu m were reported(4).",
