 "Value": {
 "StringWithMarkup": [
 {
 "String": "n-Hexane was detected in the workplace atmospheres of 336 businesses in Belgium with a frequency of occurrence of 15% for those that utilize printing pastes; 7% where painting took place; 10% of the automobile repair shops and 6% for sites where various materials such as varnishes are employed(1). A 1984 study showed n-hexane was emitted from gasoline exposing outside operators at the refineries to an average air concentration of 0.473 mg/cu m; n-hexane was detected in 54 of 56 samples(2). Transport drivers were exposed to n-hexane at atmospheric concentration of 1.019 mg/cu m and n-hexane was detected in 49 of 49 samples(2). Gas station attendants were exposed to n-hexane at atmospheric concentration of 1.175 mg/cu m and n-hexane was detected in 48 of 49 samples(3). Tank contractors were exposed to vapors containing n-hexane at concentration of 14.7 ppm at gasoline tank removal sites(3). A total of 89 employees who spray paints or glues for their jobs for 3 companies were exposed to n-hexane at an average concentration of 1.1 ppm(4). A survey of 15 different US trucking terminals between 2004 and 2005 revealed mean n-hexane concentrations of 3.05 and 2.49 cu/cu m were measured at the loading dock and mechanic shop, respectively. The mean in-cab concentration of n-hexane was 2.24 (nonsmokers; 64 observations) and 1.53 ug/cu m (smokers; 18 observations) for workers involved in pickup and delivery operations; the back ground concentration was 1.70 ug/cu m in 160 air observations(5). Trace levels were detected inside North Carolina Highway Patrol cars, determined from analysis of 25 workshifts (3PM to midnight) in autumn, 2001(6).",
