 "Value": {
 "StringWithMarkup": [
 {
 "String": "URBAN/SUBURBAN: The concentration of cyclohexane in Tulsa, OK on July 27, 1978 was 0-3.30 ppbC (ppb carbon) whereas at a rural site 37 km downwind it was 2.70 ppbC(1). Various locations in Houston, TX, including industrial areas and tunnels - 0-22.4 ppb, 9.37 ppb, mean with 9 of 16 samples postive(4). Early morning concentrations of cyclohexane in the central business district in Los Angeles in the summer and fall of 1961: 0-6 ppb, 6th floor level(5). A study of Los Angeles air carried out in the fall of 1981 reported cyclohexane concentrations ranging from 7-31 ppb(6). The average concentration of cyclohexane over a 30 day period (140 samples) in Sidney, Australia and environs was 0.9 ppb(2). The concentration of the hydrocarbons reaches a maximum at 8 AM suggesting an influence of rush hour traffic, and than falls to a minimum at 12 noon(2). Cyclohexane has been reported in the air in six Russian cities of widely different geography and climate(3). The mean (standard deviation) of cyclohexane 350-600 meters aloft over Tokyo was 0.1 (0.19) ppb(7). The mean concentration of cyclohexane in the ambient air of Porto Alegre, Brazil during March 20, 1996 to April 16, 1997 was 2.4 ug/cu m(8). Cyclohexane was one of many hydrocarbons detected in the air of Beijing, China prior to and during the 2008 Olympics (concentrations not reported)(9).",
